---
/**
 * Fula Devi. Who she was, introduced through confirmed facts, remembered
 * events and authentic family photographs. The person, not the institution.
 * No moral is drawn after a memory — readers reach their own conclusions.
 *
 * All photographs are unaltered family originals: metadata sanitized, pixels
 * untouched. No generative restoration or facial reconstruction (see
 * docs/FULA_DEVI_IMAGE_ARCHIVE.md).
 */
import ContentPage from '../layouts/ContentPage.astro';
import Figure from '../components/Figure.astro';
import Quote from '../components/Quote.astro';
---

<ContentPage
  locale="en"
  title="Fula Devi"
  description="Stories and photographs of Fula Devi, remembered for her everyday kindness, support for independence, and respect for people of different faiths."
>
  <p>
    Fula Devi (1956 – 22 July 2006) lived in Bihar, India. This institution was
    established in her memory. She was the mother of the institution's
    co-founder and the wife of its first secretary.
  </p>
  <p>
    Those who knew her remember the quiet kindness with which she treated
    people in everyday life.
  </p>

  <img
    class="portrait"
    src="/images/fula-devi/portrait/fula-devi-blue-sari-portrait.jpg"
    alt="Portrait of Fula Devi wearing a blue sari and looking toward the camera."
    width="735"
    height="1012"
    loading="eager"
    decoding="async"
  />

  <h2>She Preserved Dignity</h2>
  <p>
    During a blanket distribution organised by the institution in 2025, a
    former daily labourer who had worked for the family shared a memory from
    many years earlier.
  </p>
  <p>
    He recalled that when he came to the house at the end of each working day,
    Fula Devi fed him and repeatedly asked him to eat a little more so that he
    would not feel shy about eating enough.
  </p>

  <h2>She Helped Quietly</h2>
  <p>
    A woman who later spoke to Fula Devi's son remembered that Fula Devi would
    quietly give her whatever money she could afford and always treated her
    with respect.
  </p>

  {/* Tall photograph: capped by height rather than width so the whole frame
      stays visible without taking over the desktop viewport. */}
  <div class="tall-figure">
    <Figure
      src="/images/fula-devi/life/fula-devi-holding-painted-pot.jpg"
      alt="Fula Devi holding a decorated clay pot during her daughter's wedding ceremony."
      caption="Fula Devi holding a decorated clay pot during her daughter's wedding ceremony."
      width={848}
      height={1272}
    />
  </div>

  <h2>She Encouraged Independence</h2>
  <p>
    She encouraged her daughters to become educated and financially
    independent.
  </p>
  <p>
    She supported them in applying for demanding jobs that were often
    considered unsuitable for women at the time.
  </p>

  <h2>She Respected Every Faith</h2>
  <p>
    Although she was a deeply religious Hindu, she encouraged her children to
    learn about any religion they wished to explore.
  </p>
  <p>
    Her family remembers her saying that all gods are one and that religions
    teach the same lessons, like the same syllabus taught under different
    education boards.
  </p>

  {/* Both Kanwar Yatra photographs are shown together, without a gallery
      heading: they are one occasion, not a separate collection. */}
  <div class="gallery">
    <Figure
      src="/images/fula-devi/pilgrimage/fula-devi-kanwar-yatra-with-husband.jpg"
      alt="Fula Devi and her husband during the Kanwar Yatra pilgrimage."
      caption="Fula Devi and her husband during the Kanwar Yatra."
      width={1200}
      height={1600}
    />
    <Figure
      src="/images/fula-devi/pilgrimage/fula-devi-kanwar-yatra-group-01.jpg"
      alt="Fula Devi standing with her daughters during the Kanwar Yatra pilgrimage."
      caption="Fula Devi with her daughters during the Kanwar Yatra."
      width={1600}
      height={1200}
    />
    <p class="pilgrimage-note">
      These photographs were taken during a traditional Kanwar Yatra in which
      Fula Devi and her family walked approximately 105 km from Sultanganj to
      Deoghar while carrying holy water from the Ganges.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>A Teaching Remembered</h2>
  <p>Her family remembers her saying:</p>
  <Quote attribution="Translated into English.">
    Serve the living.<br />
    Feed others. Give water to a cow.<br />
    That's worship.
  </Quote>
</ContentPage>

<style>
  /* Page-local only — no global CSS, no new components. */

  /* The portrait sits below the title and stays subordinate to it.
     min() keeps the cap from overriding the global max-width:100%, which this
     more specific selector would otherwise beat — without it the portrait
     overflows its container on viewports narrower than about 470px. */
  .portrait {
    max-width: min(440px, 100%);
    margin-inline: auto;
  }

  /* The clay-pot photograph is much taller than it is wide. Capping its width
     would leave it running most of a desktop screen, so it is capped by height
     instead: the whole frame stays visible, uncropped and at its own aspect
     ratio, and the figure shrink-wraps to whatever width that leaves.
     max-height is inert on narrow screens, where max-width takes over. */
  .tall-figure :global(figure) {
    width: fit-content;
    max-width: 100%;
    margin-inline: auto;
  }

  .tall-figure :global(img) {
    display: block;
    width: auto;
    height: auto;
    max-width: 100%;
    max-height: min(70vh, 640px);
    object-fit: contain;
    margin-inline: auto;
  }

  /* Two columns on wider screens, one on mobile. No JS, no fixed-height
     crop: each photograph keeps its natural aspect ratio. */
  .gallery {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-6);
  }

  @media (min-width: 34rem) {
    .gallery {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
      align-items: start;
    }
  }

  /* Figures inside the grid are already spaced by the grid gap. */
  .gallery :global(figure) {
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* One note for both photographs, so the route is not repeated in each
     caption. It spans the grid and sits below both columns; quieter than a
     caption, and deliberately not a heading, quote or card. */
  .pilgrimage-note {
    grid-column: 1 / -1;
    /* The prose measure would otherwise hold it to 62ch, leaving it short of
       the second column. It spans the grid, so it is released from that cap
       here and nowhere else. */
    max-width: none;
    margin: 0;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-ink-soft);
  }
</style>
